<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="C7_Qiskit_Continued" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Qiskit Continued</title>

  <introduction>
    <p> In this chapter, we will explore more of Qiskit's functionality, and learn about how to
      represent quantum states, apply quantum gates, and perform multi-qubit operations. To do so,
      we're going to switch over to using a new third-party tool, <term>Google Colab</term>. </p>

    <p>In each of the sections in this chapter, you will see a Google Drive link to a <term>
        Jupyter notebook</term>. This is an interactive Python environment where you can follow
      along with instructions and explanations and run your code directly (much like this
      textbook!). At various points in the notebook, you will be prompted to return to the textbook
      to answer questions relating to what you have learned. </p>

    <p> For each section, follow these steps for the first time: <ul>
        <li>Open the link at the top of the section.</li>
        <li>Ensure you are signed in with your University email.</li>
        <li>Click on the button that says "Open with Google Colaboratory..." in the top-right
          corner.</li>
        <li>Once the notebook opens in Google Colab, click on the "Copy to Drive" button in the top
      toolbar.</li>
      </ul> Once you follow these steps, you will have a copy of this notebook
      saved in your Google Drive. You can now just open that up instead of going to the link at the
      top of each section. </p>
  </introduction>

